      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":57,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":342,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":342,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the relaxed end of your easy range. Let your body wake up gradually — no rushing the first few minutes.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":47,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":342,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable, conversational effort. You should be able to speak in full sentences without gasping. This is aerobic base work — resist the urge to push.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace in the final 5 minutes. Let your heart rate drift down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin at the slower end of your easy range (around 5:56/km) for the first 5 minutes. No strides, no surges — just gentle movement.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Slow to a walk for 2–3 minutes after finishing. Light calf and hip flexor stretching is a good idea given your Achilles history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run sets the tone for the week. At VDOT 46.7, your aerobic base is genuinely strong — this run is about maintaining that foundation without accumulating fatigue. Easy really does mean easy here: 5:22–5:56/km. The physiological goal is capillary development and mitochondrial maintenance, and those adaptations happen best at low intensity. Given your Achilles history, the gradual warm-up on Monday is especially worth protecting.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Cruise Intervals at Threshold\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":60,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":342,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":342,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy running to get the legs moving and core temperature up. Include 4 x 20-second strides in the final 3 minutes of the warmup — relaxed, not sprinting.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":6,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 x 6-minute cruise intervals at threshold pace (4:28/km). This should feel comfortably hard — you could speak a word or two but not hold a conversation. Each rep is its own effort; don't bank pace early.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":342,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":3,\"notes\":\"90 seconds to 2 minutes of easy jogging between each cruise interval. Keep moving — don't stop completely. This is active recovery, not rest.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog to bring heart rate down. Finish with 5 minutes of walking and dynamic stretching.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy running including 4 x 20-second relaxed strides in the final 3 minutes. The strides prime your neuromuscular system for the faster work ahead without pre-fatiguing you.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"At least 10 minutes easy jogging after the final interval. Your Achilles will thank you for a thorough cooldown — include calf raises and eccentric heel drops if that's been part of your maintenance routine.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals are one of the most effective tools for maintaining lactate threshold fitness. Four 6-minute reps at 4:28/km gives you 24 minutes of quality threshold work — enough stimulus to keep your fitness sharp without the recovery cost of a continuous tempo run. The 2-minute jog recoveries are intentional: they keep the session aerobic and prevent the workout from becoming a race. If the pace feels genuinely hard rather than comfortably hard, it's okay to dial back to 4:32–4:35/km. The goal is the stimulus, not the number.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Recovery Easy Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":48,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very gently — this is a recovery day after Tuesday's threshold work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":38,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Stay at the slower end of your easy range today (5:45–5:56/km). This is deliberate recovery running. If your legs feel heavy from Tuesday, that's normal and expected — trust the process.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Finish gently. Walk the last 2 minutes if you like.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed beyond starting slowly. The whole run is essentially a warmup pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes after finishing. This is a great day for foam rolling and light mobility work, especially around the calves and Achilles.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday follows a quality session, so the goal here is active recovery — flushing metabolic byproducts and maintaining movement without adding meaningful stress. Running at the slower end of your easy range (closer to 5:56/km) is genuinely productive on days like this. The temptation to push a little is real, especially for experienced runners, but the adaptation from Tuesday's threshold work happens during recovery, not during the next hard effort. Eight kilometers is enough to keep the aerobic engine ticking without digging into your reserves.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":65,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":342,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":342,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy running. Include 4–6 x 20-second strides in the final 3 minutes to prime your legs for the faster work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":251,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 1000m at interval pace (4:11/km). This is hard — you should be working at roughly 95–98% of max HR by the end of each rep. Controlled aggression: don't sprint the first 200m. Even splits are the goal.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"2–3 minutes easy jog between each 1000m rep. Enough recovery to run the next rep at full quality — not so much that you go completely cold.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":342,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging after the final rep. This is non-negotiable — your cardiovascular system needs time to come down safely.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"A thorough 15-minute warmup is essential before interval work. Include dynamic leg swings, hip circles, and 4–6 x 20-second strides. Your body needs to be genuinely warm before you ask it to run at 4:11/km.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging minimum. Finish with calf stretches and eccentric heel drops — Thursday is a high-stress day for the Achilles tendon, so post-run care matters here.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the sharpest tool in the maintenance toolkit. Five 1000m reps at 4:11/km develops and preserves your aerobic ceiling — the fitness that makes everything else feel easier. At VDOT 46.7, this pace is appropriately challenging without being reckless. The key execution cue: start each rep feeling like you could go faster, and finish each rep feeling like you couldn't have gone much further. If you're dying after rep 3, the pace is too aggressive — dial back to 4:15/km and complete all 5. Volume of quality work matters more than hitting an exact split.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Rest or Very Easy Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":0,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Optional: 20–30 minutes of very easy running or walking only if your legs feel genuinely good. If there is any residual fatigue or tightness — especially around the Achilles — take the full rest day. This is not a test of toughness.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"If you run: start with 5 minutes of walking before jogging. No strides, no surges.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes after any running. Prioritize mobility work, foam rolling, and sleep tonight — Saturday's long run is tomorrow.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday is a deliberate buffer between Thursday's hard interval session and Sunday's long run. Rest is not a gap in training — it is where adaptation happens. Your body has absorbed two quality sessions this week (threshold Tuesday, intervals Thursday) and needs time to consolidate those gains. If you feel restless, a 20–30 minute walk or very easy jog is fine. But if there's any tightness in the left Achilles or general fatigue, full rest is the smarter investment. You've been running 12 years — you know the difference between productive discomfort and a warning sign.\",\"perceived_effort\":1},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":342,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start gently. You're priming the legs for tomorrow's long run, not adding stress.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":342,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable easy running at 5:22–5:40/km. Relaxed, rhythmic, enjoyable. This is a feel-good run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":322,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":6,\"notes\":\"6 x 20-second strides at the end of the run. Relaxed acceleration to about 5:22/km — not sprinting. 60 seconds easy walking/jogging between each. These keep your legs feeling sharp and neuromuscularly primed for Sunday.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":6,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog and walk to finish. Keep it brief — save your legs for tomorrow.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start easy and stay easy. The strides at the end are the only uptempo element — everything else is gentle aerobic running.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Brief cooldown — 5 minutes easy jog, then walk. Hydrate well tonight and eat a carbohydrate-containing meal in the evening to top up glycogen for Sunday's long run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday's run serves two purposes: maintaining aerobic volume and priming the neuromuscular system for Sunday's long run. The 6 x 20-second strides at the end are a well-researched pre-activation tool — they wake up fast-twitch fibers and improve running economy without adding meaningful fatigue. Keep the main body of the run genuinely easy. The goal is to arrive at Sunday's long run feeling fresh, not depleted. Hydration and carbohydrate intake tonight will matter more than anything you do in this run.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":112,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":342,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes at the very easy end of your range (5:50–5:56/km). Resist the urge to settle into pace too quickly on long runs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":72,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":342,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Main body of the long run at 5:22–5:40/km. Conversational effort throughout. If you're running with someone, you should be able to hold a full conversation. If you're alone, the effort should feel like you could run another hour.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":322,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Optional: final 4–5 km at a slightly brisker pace — around 5:22/km or a touch faster. This is only if you feel genuinely strong in the final third. Do not force this progression if you're working hard to maintain pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 10 minutes back to easy pace. Finish the run feeling like you had something left — that's the goal.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start at 5:50–5:56/km for the first 10 minutes. Long runs are notorious for starting too fast — the first 3 km should feel almost embarrassingly easy.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5–10 minutes after finishing. Prioritize refueling within 30–45 minutes (carbohydrates and protein). Light stretching of calves, hip flexors, and hamstrings. Given your Achilles history, eccentric heel drops post-long run are a worthwhile habit.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the cornerstone of your aerobic fitness. At 20 km, this is well within your current capacity (you ran 21 km last week) and sits comfortably within your 120-minute cap. The optional progression in the final 4–5 km is a maintenance tool — it teaches your body to run efficiently on tired legs, which is exactly the stimulus that keeps marathon fitness sharp even without a race on the horizon. The key word is optional: if you're working to maintain easy pace at km 16, skip the progression entirely and finish strong at easy effort. A long run where you finish feeling controlled is worth far more than one where you grind out the last 5 km. Your weekly total this week lands around 53–55 km, consistent with your recent training history and well within safe progression guidelines.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
